PROFESSOR: The norm squared
gives you the probabilities.

00:32:07.952 --> 00:32:09.410
But if you know
the coefficients---

00:32:09.410 --> 00:32:10.380
so this is a good question.

00:32:10.380 --> 00:32:11.713
So let me rephrase the question.

00:32:11.713 --> 00:32:16.230
The question is, in the
previous question we said,

00:32:16.230 --> 00:32:19.280
our wave function phi of
x is some function which

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:20.257
we could draw.

00:32:20.257 --> 00:32:21.840
So I could represent
this in two ways.

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:24.160
I could either draw it,
or I could represent

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:27.635
it as equal the sum
over n of cn phi

00:32:27.635 --> 00:32:30.620
n where phi n are the
known energy functions.

00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:34.109
And the question is, did the cn
contain the same information?

00:32:34.109 --> 00:32:35.150
So that was the question.

00:32:35.150 --> 00:32:37.030
And the point that's
being asked about here

00:32:37.030 --> 00:32:38.210
is a very good question.

00:32:38.210 --> 00:32:41.720
The question is, look, we
know what these cn's mean.

00:32:41.720 --> 00:32:43.940
What the cn's mean
is the probability

00:32:43.940 --> 00:32:45.575
that you measure
the energy-- given

00:32:45.575 --> 00:32:47.950
that the state of psi, the
probability [INAUDIBLE] energy

00:32:47.950 --> 00:32:51.920
En is equal to norm cn squared.

00:32:51.920 --> 00:32:54.147
And so the cn's tell
you about probabilities.

00:32:54.147 --> 00:32:55.730
They don't tell you
what the state is.

00:32:55.730 --> 00:32:56.860
They just tell you
what a probability

00:32:56.860 --> 00:32:58.150
is that you'll measure
a particular energy.

00:32:58.150 --> 00:32:59.180
Is that right?

00:32:59.180 --> 00:33:02.442
So how can it contain
the same information?

00:33:02.442 --> 00:33:04.650
And there are two important
things to say about this.

00:33:04.650 --> 00:33:07.190
First off, this
is of course true.

00:33:07.190 --> 00:33:08.871
And this does give
you the probability.

00:33:08.871 --> 00:33:10.870
And the probability comes
from the norm squared.

00:33:10.870 --> 00:33:14.430
So the phase of cn doesn't
particularly matter for that.

00:33:14.430 --> 00:33:17.800
However the claim that I
can expand this function

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:21.140
in a basis of the
energy eigenfunctions,

00:33:21.140 --> 00:33:23.740
in a basis of other
functions, is a statement

00:33:23.740 --> 00:33:27.130
that if know these cn's, then
I take c1 multiplied by phi 1,

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:29.810
c2 multiplied by phi 2,
add them all back up,

00:33:29.810 --> 00:33:33.490
and I get nothing other
than this original function.

00:33:33.490 --> 00:33:35.690
So if I know the
cn's, I can just

00:33:35.690 --> 00:33:39.780
construct that original
function explicitly.

00:33:39.780 --> 00:33:43.130
So this can't contain
any more or any less

00:33:43.130 --> 00:33:45.230
information than the
list of cn's, as long

00:33:45.230 --> 00:33:47.690
as I know what basis
I'm talking about.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:49.750
So here's the disturbing
thing about that.

00:33:49.750 --> 00:33:52.960
When we say the wave function
is the state of the system--

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:56.290
it contains all knowledge you
could possibly have access to.

00:33:56.290 --> 00:33:58.600
And not just knowledge that
you could have access to,

00:33:58.600 --> 00:34:00.877
it contains all of the
information of the state.

00:34:00.877 --> 00:34:02.710
And then we look at
this and say, well look,

00:34:02.710 --> 00:34:03.970
it doesn't give us
something deterministic.

00:34:03.970 --> 00:34:05.270
It gives us something
probabilistic.

00:34:05.270 --> 00:34:06.780
It tells us the
probability distribution

00:34:06.780 --> 00:34:08.440
for measuring the various
different energies.

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:09.719
