And sometimes it's useful to
call it c, for commutator.

01:11:30.050 --> 01:11:31.650
So it gives you a new operator.

01:11:31.650 --> 01:11:33.630
Given two operators you
build a new operator.

01:11:36.280 --> 01:11:41.600
And suppose now that we
have a common eigenfunction

01:11:41.600 --> 01:11:42.270
of a and b.

01:11:42.270 --> 01:11:43.270
What does that tell you?

01:11:43.270 --> 01:11:47.920
Well, let's take the
commutator-- a, b--

01:11:47.920 --> 01:11:50.380
and let's take it and
act on phi of sub ab

01:11:50.380 --> 01:11:51.839
on this common eigenstate.

01:11:51.839 --> 01:11:52.880
So what is this equal to?

01:11:52.880 --> 01:12:00.060
This is equal to ab
minus ba phi b, which

01:12:00.060 --> 01:12:06.550
I can write as ab phi
ab minus ba phi ab

01:12:06.550 --> 01:12:11.020
by linearity-- by
addition, really.

01:12:11.020 --> 01:12:15.390
But b acting on phi ab gives
me, by hypothesis, little b.

01:12:18.630 --> 01:12:21.650
And then a acting on a
constant times phi ab

01:12:21.650 --> 01:12:26.060
gives me a little a times
that constant minus-- now

01:12:26.060 --> 01:12:29.370
here a acting on phi ab
gives me little a phi ab.

01:12:29.370 --> 01:12:34.190
And then b acting on constant
times phi ab gives me little b.

01:12:34.190 --> 01:12:35.750
And now I can join
these together.

01:12:35.750 --> 01:12:43.030
This is equal to little
ab minus ba phi ab.

01:12:48.300 --> 01:12:50.460
But little a and
little b are numbers.

01:12:50.460 --> 01:12:53.380
If you take 7 times 5 and 5
times 7 and you subtract them,

01:12:53.380 --> 01:12:55.230
what do you get?

01:12:55.230 --> 01:12:56.210
0.

01:12:56.210 --> 01:13:03.887
So in order for a and b to share
a single eigenfunction phi ab,

01:13:03.887 --> 01:13:05.470
what must be true
of their commutator?

01:13:08.390 --> 01:13:10.990
It must have an a
non-zero kernel, exactly.

01:13:10.990 --> 01:13:15.400
The commutator must annihilate
that particular common

01:13:15.400 --> 01:13:16.940
eigenfunction.

01:13:16.940 --> 01:13:19.380
Does it tell you that
it kills every function?

01:13:19.380 --> 01:13:21.000
No.

01:13:21.000 --> 01:13:24.570
But it must at the very
least annihilate the shared

01:13:24.570 --> 01:13:25.375
eigenfunction.

01:13:25.375 --> 01:13:25.875
True?

01:13:28.920 --> 01:13:35.490
Consider two operators
of the following form.

01:13:35.490 --> 01:13:40.370
Consider two operators
who commutator ab

01:13:40.370 --> 01:13:43.245
is equal to the identity
times a constant.

01:13:47.800 --> 01:13:52.650
Do these operators share
any common eigenfunctions?

01:13:52.650 --> 01:13:56.090
They can't, because the
commutator-- the identity--

01:13:56.090 --> 01:13:58.980
doesn't annihilate
any wave functions.

01:13:58.980 --> 01:14:00.130
Any functions.

01:14:00.130 --> 01:14:02.510
Nothing is 0 when acted
upon by the identity.

01:14:02.510 --> 01:14:05.490
That's the definition
of the identity.

01:14:05.490 --> 01:14:11.290
The identity takes any function,
gives it that function back.

01:14:11.290 --> 01:14:12.920
Cool?

01:14:12.920 --> 01:14:16.050
Do a and b share any
common eigenfunctions?

01:14:16.050 --> 01:14:22.010
Now let's think about what that
means in terms of observables.

01:14:22.010 --> 01:14:25.700
Observables are
represented by operators.

01:14:25.700 --> 01:14:28.614
What is the meaning
of the eigenfunctions

01:14:28.614 --> 01:14:29.405
of those operators?

01:14:34.560 --> 01:14:36.510
AUDIENCE: It corresponds
to the [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:36.510 --> 01:14:39.070
