corresponds to the state

01:14:39.070 --> 01:14:41.580
with a definite value
of that observable.

01:14:41.580 --> 01:14:46.040
And the value is the
corresponding eigenvalue.

01:14:46.040 --> 01:14:49.570
So the eigenfunction of
an observable operator

01:14:49.570 --> 01:14:51.882
is a possible state
with a definite value

01:14:51.882 --> 01:14:52.590
of that operator.

01:14:52.590 --> 01:14:54.756
If I tell you that I have
a state which is an energy

01:14:54.756 --> 01:14:56.280
eigenfunction,
then that means it

01:14:56.280 --> 01:14:58.420
is a state with a definite
value of the energy.

01:14:58.420 --> 01:15:01.510
If I measure that energy, I
know exactly what I will get.

01:15:01.510 --> 01:15:03.240
Cool?

01:15:03.240 --> 01:15:07.560
If a and b are two observables
and their commutator

01:15:07.560 --> 01:15:11.510
is proportional to the
identity, is it possible

01:15:11.510 --> 01:15:13.690
that there is a state
with a definite value

01:15:13.690 --> 01:15:18.140
of a and a definite value
of b simultaneously?

01:15:18.140 --> 01:15:20.060
No, because a state with
a definite value of a

01:15:20.060 --> 01:15:21.351
would be an eigenfunction of a.

01:15:21.351 --> 01:15:22.970
And a state with a
definite value of b

01:15:22.970 --> 01:15:24.470
would be an eigenfunction of b.

01:15:24.470 --> 01:15:28.410
And there are no common states,
no common eigenfunctions

01:15:28.410 --> 01:15:33.590
of a and b because the
commutator never kills a state.

01:15:33.590 --> 01:15:34.420
It has no 0's.

